<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="inv-5-7">
  <title>Investigation 5.7: Drive for Show, Putt for Dough</title>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises5-7" hidden-label="yes">
    <title>The Study</title>

    <p>This investigation compares how PGA scoring average relates to driving distance and putting average using <c>golfers18.txt</c>.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-a" label="I5.7.a"><title>Direction Conjecture: Driving</title><statement><p>(a) Predict direction of association between scoring average and driving distance.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Negative, golfers that hit further will tend to be the same golfers with lower scores.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-b" label="I5.7.b"><title>Direction Conjecture: Putting</title><statement><p>(b) Predict direction of association between scoring average and putting average.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Positive, golfers that hit more putts will tend to be the same golfers with higher scores.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-c" label="I5.7.c"><title>Compare Scatterplots</title><statement><p>(c) Produce both scatterplots and compare direction, form, and strength.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The relationship between average score and average driving distance does appear to be negative. The relationship between average score and putting average appears positive and to be stronger than the first relationship. (Both graphs have some outliers worth investigating.)</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-d" label="I5.7.d"><title>Quadrant Reasoning</title><statement><p>(d) With mean lines shown, identify aligned vs non-aligned quadrants for both plots.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>average score vs. average putts has more points in quadrants I and III.</p><p>average score vs. driving has more points in quadrants II and IV.</p><p>There appear to be fewer "unaligned points" in the average score vs. average putts graph.</p></solution></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Definition: Correlation Coefficient</title>
      <p>The correlation coefficient <m>r</m> measures strength and direction of a linear relationship and is unitless.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-e" label="I5.7.e"><title>Units of r</title><statement><p>(e) Use the formula to determine the units of <m>r</m> for putts vs strokes.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>no measurement units.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-f" label="I5.7.f"><title>Interpret r=0</title><statement><p>(f) If correlation equals zero, what might the scatterplot look like?</p></statement><response/><solution><p>the points will have random scatter, observations with below average <m>x</m> values will have both below and above average <m>y</m> values, observations with above average <m>x</m> values will have both below and above average <m>y</m> values.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-g" label="I5.7.g"><title>Correlation with Itself</title><statement><p>(g) What is the correlation of a variable with itself?</p></statement><response/><solution><p>1.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-h" label="I5.7.h"><title>Resistance</title><statement><p>(h) Is correlation resistant to outliers? Explain.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>no, involves means, standard deviations, and squared terms, all of which should contribute to it not being resistant to outliers.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-i" label="I5.7.i"><title>Rank Correlations from Plots</title><statement><p>(i) Rank provided scatterplots from strongest negative to strongest positive correlation.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>rankings may vary.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-j" label="I5.7.j"><title>Compute Correlations with Technology</title><statement><p>(j) Compute and record correlation coefficients for each plot pair using applet/R/JMP.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Example values from strongest negative to strongest positive: -0.819, -0.765, -0.451, -0.090, 0.485, 0.632, 0.888.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-k" label="I5.7.k"><title>Range of r</title><statement><p>(k) State smallest and largest possible values of <m>r</m>.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>smallest in absolute value: 0, largest in absolute value: 1.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-l" label="I5.7.l"><title>Sign of r</title><statement><p>(l) What sign of <m>r</m> corresponds to negative vs positive association?</p></statement><response/><solution><p><m>r</m> will be negative when the association is negative and positive if the association is positive.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-m" label="I5.7.m"><title>Meaning of r near 0</title><statement><p>(m) What does <m>r</m> near zero signify?</p></statement><response/><solution><p>no (linear) association.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-n" label="I5.7.n"><title>Meaning of r near +-1</title><statement><p>(n) What does <m>r</m> close to 1 or -1 signify?</p></statement><response/><solution><p>perfect linear relationship.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-o" label="I5.7.o"><title>Cliche Check</title><statement><p>(o) Which variable has stronger correlation with scoring average: driving distance or putting average? Does this support the cliche?</p></statement><response/><solution><p>scoring average and putting average which does support the cliche that putting is more related to overall scoring than driving distance.</p></solution></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Study Conclusions</title>
      <p>The putting relationship with scoring average is typically stronger than the driving relationship in these data. Correlation quantifies linear association and should always be interpreted alongside scatterplots.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-practice-a" label="I5.7A"><title>Practice Problem 5.7A</title><statement><p>Reason about correlation when final exam scores are fixed transformations of midterm scores.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-practice-b" label="I5.7B"><title>Practice Problem 5.7B</title><statement><p>Match house-price scatterplots to correlation values and justify.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>
